<subSubSection id="C30EB4BB83717E0EA3C0F9FDB5C46A4C" pageId="7" pageNumber="218" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BABE73083717E0EA3C0F9FDB5C46A4C" blockId="7.[151,1437,1636,2023]" pageId="7" pageNumber="218">
<emphasis id="B9603B2283717E0EA3C0F9FDB72F6B00" bold="true" box="[151,274,1636,1662]" pageId="7" pageNumber="218">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is recognized within the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C149CB383717E0EA056F9FDB5A46B00" authorityName="Fieber" authorityYear="1860" baseAuthorityName="Fieber" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[769,921,1636,1662]" class="Insecta" family="Alydidae" genus="Megalotomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="218" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9603B2283717E0EA056F9FDB5A46B00" box="[769,921,1636,1662]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="218">Megalotomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by a combination of the following characters: body relatively large, 15.0–17.0 mm in length, mostly brownish in colour; vertex black, with pale yellow midline; pronotum divided into two lobes by colour, with anterior lobe black, and posterior lobe reddish brown; posterior angles of pronotum acute and pointed, with a sharp apex; surcapsular spines of the genital capsule slightly curving, each one with a broad spine at outer margin of proximal part and a small bifurcation at apex; parameres wide and curving, each one with a conspicuous longitudinal crease at the terminal half.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
